\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Morning came to Mandri like a brick. Not a hangover, it was the heavy lethargy of the deepest sleep. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He sat up, stretched his arms, and found himself back in the original temple basement. How he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d gotten there, he did not know. The previous night was a feverish sleep, and he wondered if his journey with the god\u8217\'92s eye burgeon was but a frightful dream. And he couldn\u8217\'92t have dreamed up what those burgeons had made him see.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He closed his eyes and tried to remember.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There was some kind of geometric pattern, shimmering lines of immanence extending out from his eyes.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 And then\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 And then\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 And then he realized that he was alone.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He opened his eyes again and saw that not a single Ayramun was present. Not even Obo was there, only the ashy coals of the fire, and the lingering smell of smoke.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri startled to, jumped up, thinking he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d been left behind. His sleep crusted eyes were able to filter through the dim blue light of morning and see that the Ayramun\u8217\'92s packs were still there. He hadn\u8217\'92t been left behind, he\u8217\'92d been left out.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He looked around and saw that the hole in the wall that he and Seb had passed through in the night was indeed there. He figured that maybe the Ayramun had gone into it, to some secret chamber, but as he didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t have a light to follow, he decided instead to climb the ladder and see what was going on outside.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He hoped they were up there having breakfast. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He climbed up the ladder\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s rungs and found that his legs were remarkably lively. Only a hint of the soreness that he\u8217\'92d been dreading.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Must have been the burgeons. He decided to ask Seb about it once he got the chance, and maybe ask how he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d ended up . Maybe it was best to pretend that he remembered everything, including walking back himself, because he didn\u8217\'92t want to give Seb the idea that he couldn\u8217\'92t handle those burgeons. He wanted to try them again.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 When he pulled himself up onto the cobbled stone of the temple floor.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There was no altar or kneeling stone. Only that hole in the ground with the ladder. Maybe there was a dead desert father in a crypt down below. Before Mandri could wonder too long, he heard faint voices whispering the air.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He stepped out of the temple and onto the sandy dirt, and he saw, on top a hill to the west, the Ayramun. The were all there, standing with backs turned, facing the wrong way if they wanted to watch the rising sun.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri scrambled up the hill to join them, and as soon ,}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There appeared a heavy cloud in the distant west, which was black towards the horizon, but this cloud was a churning pillar, a super-cell the size of several mountains, and its upper reaches pierced the shadow of world\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s edge and so that the sunlight lit it red against the fading of the night.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri gasped at the awesome magnificence. Little westwind zephyrs tickled his skin, and this humbling awe he was faded into a prickling terror as he realized the storm was coming right for him. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Holy shit,\u8221\'94 he muttered.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Seb was standing next to him, and he chuckled. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes, it\u8217\'92s quite a development, isn\u8217\'92t it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was more than a development. It was the mythical Mukghal, the vengeful wind. It was a favorite subject for many a desert landscape painter. And though there were many, the images they made all came out looking the same - walls of sand in lurid purple, lit up by jagged spears of lightning. Twisting funnels creeping down towards the ground, in the foreground, a sympathetic figure, a human or a green, trembling tree. The point to put the audience there, to suggest the scale, because naturally, the meager frame of the canvas could not truly mimic the real thing.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri always accepted that these painting had a certain appeal, but he also always suspected that the reason all of these paintings fit a certain style was because none of these artists had actually seen a Mukghal with their own eyes, and so they were just copying eachother. What Mandri saw before him now would stun the world if put down in paint.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But this was nature. It couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t be put down in paint. Even if it could, it\u8217\'92d still be missing the scale. The absurd scale. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Obo was there up on that hill, sitting next to Seb. He was as taken by the sight of the Mukghal as everyone else.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That is unnatural,\u8221\'94 he said. Mandri looked at Obo and saw a seriousness in the Mazyd\u8217\'92s expression that he didn\u8217\'92t think was possible.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Seb hocked a wad of borcandi juice at Obo\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s robes. He said, \u8220\'93Of course it\u8217\'92s natural. Everything that happens is natural.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Obo was undeterred. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s coming from an impossible direction.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto looked down at Obo, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What would you know about it?\u8221\'94 he asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ve read every book and scroll that accounts the weather in this part of the world, and every Mukghal for the past thousand years was born abreast the Gonigal Sea. They form when the high Gohal winds stop blowing - it\u8217\'92s like taking the lid off a pot of steaming water. And the Gonigal Sea is four days to the south. And that\u8217\'92s not to mention that Mukghals certainly don\u8217\'92t look like that.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto was unimpressed. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Clearly, they do look like that.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Have you ever been caught in a Mukghal?\u8221\'94 Obo asked him.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No. Have you?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I have. And it wasn\u8217\'92t a solid wall of sand racing across the desert. The first thing I knew of it was when my own dust overtook me. Then it was a mist of sand, and as it rolled by I was swallowed up in red haze, and what\u8217\'92s more is that I survived it. If I\u8217\'92d been caught in a thing like that, then the whipping sand would have lashed the flesh from my bones.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93All those books in Jeket, and I guess you don\u8217\'92t know shit.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Tell me, how should such a storm take form over mountains? I\u8217\'92d be interested to hear how you finesse this discrepency.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was Elrahet who answered. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It formed in the west because it\u8217\'92s not a Mukghal.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto looked at the witch with bewildered eyes, and asked, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s not?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s not,\u8221\'94 Elrahet grumbled, and then she turned her back on the storm and everyone else and began to waddle down the hill.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What is it?\u8221\'94 Moto asked, but she didn\u8217\'92t deign to answer.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto turned to Ayram.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What is it?\u8221\'94 he asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram, who\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d been brooding at the sight of the great storm, grunted, then said, \u8220\'93If Elrahet knows, and no one else does, then it\u8217\'92s probably got to do with the blood-ripe stomachs.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What are we going to do?\u8221\'94 Moteah asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Seb said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We can\u8217\'92t possibly travel with that storm on our heels.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram gave Seb annoyed tsk, despite the fact that he agreed.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We\u8217\'92ll stay down in the hole and pray these hills don\u8217\'92t get swallowed up by sand.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That would throw off our timing. Hrks might reach the before us.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They might.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Purl said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We could always try the paths under the earth.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Elrahet, who had made it down to the bottom of the hill, heard what Purl said, and shouted back, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No tunnels!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Seb said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93There\u8217\'92s got to be another way.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We could try for the Kari plain,\u8221\'94 said Moto.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram shook his head and stroked his beard.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Could try the Goree Pass,\u8221\'94 said Seb.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The Goree Pass\u8230\'85\u8221\'94 Ayram muttered, his fingers twirling the tips of his beard like they were weaving a fresh idea. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The Goree will never work,\u8221\'94 said Moto.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It could work.\u8221\'94 said Seb. Mandri waited for the grungy man to expound upon his argument, but Seb just stood there and looked at Ayram like a dog waiting to be fed.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If those demon children can track the Mazyd from anywhere, then they\u8217\'92ll sense his coming and be at the Goree Pass long before we get there.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram was now clawing at his beard. Mandri was amazed at how the hairs sprung back into that bread-loaf shape.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Maybe they won\u8217\'92t,\u8221\'94 Ayram said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why wouldn\u8217\'92t they?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If this storm curves north once it passes, then it\u8217\'92ll get in their way.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What if it doesn\u8217\'92t curve north?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then we\u8217\'92ll have to think of something else.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 With that, Ayram turned and side-step-shuffled down the hill, and Moto stamped after him like a little brother.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Of the rest of the Ayramun, Moteah seemed most unaffected by current events. She was sitting at the hill\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s crest, side-legged, with one hand locked in support, and the other drawing shapes in the sand. She\u8217\'92d do a little doodle and then watch the wind whip it away.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Seb was watching the storm with a rapacious grin. It was odd , but that\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s how it was, the man looked like he wanted to be inside that storm.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Purl was sitting next to Moteah, cross-legged, taking in the wind, squinting as she did, her brown, sun-kissed hair blowing past her shoulders to reveal the cutest little ear. Mandri thought she looked quite fine in her quiet contemplation. There were clearly thoughts running through her head, and that\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s something that\u8217\'92s difficult to capture. Too often a portrait ends up making a person look like a block of painted wood or a Sparkless husk. Eyes end up belying nothing in particular, staring at the viewer with the blankness of a cat. To combat this, Mandri liked to give the sitter a clear and cogent thought, it didn\u8217\'92t have to be anything grand, something simple that he could will into the persons face so that they ended up looking like a bright and living thing. Simple things like, \u8220\'93I can\u8217\'92t wait to eat that tomato,\u8221\'94 or, \u8220\'93\u8221\'94 Some sitters didn\u8217\'92t need it, especially those who\u8217\'92d mastered the art of looking serious, as Purl had. Purl had mastered the art of looking serious, and gods, that was sexy as hell.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 That last thought came to as a surprise. It was the first libidinous thought he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d had since he\u8217\'92d risen from the dead. Perhaps that meant the succor of salt that Moteah had snuck int his food was wearing off.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Anyone else hungry?\u8221\'94 Mandri asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ve got some sticks in my bag,\u8221\'94 said Moteah.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Do you have anything green?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Green, like what?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t know. Something pulled from the earth instead of backed.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Seb winked and said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I do.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Seb grinned, scraggled beard, then took off for the temple and mandri made pursuit. }
