\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The roar of sand in the air was tremendous, and every now and then a gust of wind would and blow through the temple entrance and swirl around inside, and as it did, it blew though the hole in flower as if it were the hole of a flute, and the sound was whistling whine that through the cave like the labored fits of a pregnant dog.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 As the wind intensified, whine became a monotonous hum, a sound so annoying that all the Ayramun retreated further into the cave to get some sleep. Only Mandrameen and Obo stayed. Obo couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t be bothered by anything, and Mandri was mesmerized by the sight and sound of the sandstorm\u8217\'92s fury. To him it was intoxicating, being so near to such an awesome power.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He asked Obo, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93How long do you think I could last up there?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Exposed, you would die in minutes.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri walked over to the ladder and the moment he put his foot on the bottom rung, Obo asked, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re not trying to kill yourself, are you?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I want to see what it feels like. And I want to see it\u8217\'92s insides.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It will feel like torture, and it will look like nothing at all.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri continued on to climb, and when he got to the top, he stuck his hand up to test the air.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Sand blasted into his palm like a hundred bee stings.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Agghh! God damn! That hurts.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Obo laughed. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Told you so.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri climbed back down and sat near the fire, massaging his prickled hand. Red welts the size of pinpricks dotted it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I can\u8217\'92t believe they\u8217\'92re trying to kill Solraheen,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93If He could make this storm, then just imagine the kind of power He has.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Solraheen didn\u8217\'92t make this storm,\u8221\'94 Obo said. \u8220\'93As I\u8217\'92m sure you are aware, He is incapacitated at the moment.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93He might not have made this particular storm, but He made\u8230\'85 you know\u8230\'85 he made the structure for it. The possibility for it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You think of him as a designer.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes, and it\u8217\'92s pure creativity, not the impression of creativityLike when artists work, we\u8217\'92re just moving things around. Like Moto was saying earlier about swordplay - his medium is movement. A painter just moves paint around. None of it is real creativity. What it is, is manipulation. But Solraheen, he created the wind, he created the sand, and from these, he created this storm. And why would anyone want to kill a being that could do that? That kind of creativity is the only thing that makes life worth living.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri, Solraheen is not a god.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri laughed. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What is he, then?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m quite sure, but by my definition, God is that which is necessary, and tell me, if Solraheen were a necessary being, then could he be killed?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m not going to answer that question, because I think the premise is a load of shit.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Obo pressed on, and asked the question again. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Do you think Solraheen can be killed?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Look forget I asked. I don\u8217\'92t really care about what you believe.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why not? If I were human, would you care then?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Probably not.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Everyone thinks that because I don\u8217\'92t have a Spark, that means I\u8217\'92m incapable of faith, or belief. But I do believe in something.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 "What?"}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 "How?"}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8223\'22OUch?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I believe that there exists a thing which lies outside the bounds of logic and reason, beyond understanding. You might call it the Demiurge, or the the Uncaused Cause, or God. I am not certain of it\u8217\'92s existence, but I believe that it is there, because I, too, am forced to confront the simple absurdity of existence.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You mean like when you close your eyes and think about how everything would make so much more sense if nothing existed at all?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Obo nodded. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93A pure sea of nothingness. A void, with no people, no earth, no Solraheen. Nothing sprouting up. No being.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Indulging that feeling is a bit childish, isn\u8217\'92t it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Not at all.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m not going to get into it with you.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri got up and fashioned some pillows out of what packs had been left in the room. He gave a quick look for Seb\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s pack, because a drop of God\u8217\'92s Eye would significantly improve the day, but of course Seb had probably expected this and brought his pack with him. So, Mandri was forced to lay there sober and watch the hole and listen to raging of the storm.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He could hear the sand scratching at the bricks.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He could hear excited whispers coming from the Ayramun.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 An hour passed hour like this, and all the while the winds outside were rising. The gusts were getting so strong that over the wind\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s howl and the sizzle of the sand, there was the unmistakable grind of rock sliding atop rock.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri looked to Obo, and who seemed unconcerned.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The wind is lifting the dome,\u8221\'94 Obo said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Should we be in here?\u8221\'94 Mandri asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I think we should be fine, but my forecasts have been wrong of late.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri stood up and backed away from the hole, and as he did, an especially forceful gust blew into the temple above, sending such a shrill whistle that stressed the acoustic , but only for , for it was silenced by the crashing of stone. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A wisp of sand fell down, as if it were the dying breath of that great sand storm. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The whistle and concomitant collapse had caused all the Ayramun to stir.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was Ayram who first came bu.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Now that the howling wind was gone, the Ayramun filtered back into the pitted room.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Brooding Ayram kept him company. Ayram , as the storm ground down the rocks above. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It took a full day for the storm to past, and in it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s dying wake, Ayram climbed up the ladder with his spud bar and punched a hole into the fallen dome. A stream of sand came pouring down, but Ayram persisted through it and banged his spudbar around, widening the whole, until a great avalanche dumped down.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s firm grip kept him locked place, and once the pour had subsided, climbed up and out, then called his people to join him.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 When Mandri emerged into the fresh desert air, he was stunned to find himself at the bottom of a conical pit. Ayram was standing out alone, trying to reckon the storms track.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He said it was headed north to northeast, and that they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d be making for the Goree Pass.}
